📁 File and Directory Management
    1. ls – List directory contents
    2. cd – Change directory
    3. pwd – Show current directory
    4. mkdir – Create a new directory
    5. rmdir – Remove empty directory
    6. rm – Remove files/directories
    7. cp – Copy files/directories
    8. mv – Move/rename files
    9. touch – Create a new empty file
    10. stat – Show file info
    11. file – Determine file type
    12. basename – Strip directory and suffix
    13. dirname – Extract directory path
    14. tree – Show directory tree structure
    15. find – Search files in directory tree
    16. locate – Find files using database
    17. updatedb – Update locate DB
    18. realpath – Show absolute path
    19. lsblk – List block devices
    20. mount / umount – Mount/unmount devices

🔍 Search and Text Processing
    21. grep – Search inside files
    22. egrep – Extended grep (regex)
    23. fgrep – Fixed string grep
    24. sed – Stream editor (replace/edit text)
    25. awk – Pattern scanning and processing
    26. cut – Remove sections from lines
    27. sort – Sort lines
    28. uniq – Remove duplicates
    29. tr – Translate characters
    30. wc – Word/line/byte count
    31. head – First N lines
    32. tail – Last N lines
    33. diff – Compare files line-by-line
    34. cmp – Compare files byte-by-byte
    35. xargs – Build argument list from input
    36. strings – Print readable strings from binaries
    37. nl – Number lines
    38. tee – Read and write simultaneously

📦 Permissions and Ownership
    39. chmod – Change file permissions
    40. chown – Change file owner/group
    41. chgrp – Change group
    42. umask – Set default permissions
    43. ls -l – View file permissions
    44. getfacl / setfacl – Get/set ACLs

🖥️ Process Management
    45. ps – View running processes
    46. top / htop – Real-time process monitor
    47. kill – Kill process by PID
    48. killall – Kill by name
    49. nice / renice – Set process priority
    50. jobs – Show background jobs
    51. fg / bg – Foreground/background jobs
    52. & – Run command in background
    53. nohup – Run ignoring hangups

🧠 System Information
    54. uname -a – Kernel/system info
    55. uptime – How long the system has been running
    56. hostname – System hostname
    57. df -h – Disk space
    58. du -sh – Directory size
    59. free -h – RAM usage
    60. vmstat – Memory and CPU info
    61. iostat – I/O stats
    62. lscpu – CPU architecture
    63. lsmem – Memory info
    64. whoami – Current user
    65. id – UID, GID
    66. groups – Group memberships

🌐 Networking
    67. ping – Test connectivity
    68. curl – HTTP client
    69. wget – Download from web
    70. netstat / ss – Network stats
    71. ip a / ifconfig – Network interfaces
    72. ip r / route – Routing table
    73. nslookup / dig – DNS lookup
    74. traceroute – Trace network path
    75. nmap – Network scan
    76. scp – Secure file copy
    77. rsync – File sync (over SSH too)

📚 Other Essentials
    78. history – Show command history
    79. alias / unalias – Create/remove command shortcuts
    80. man / --help – Read manual/help for commands

